long_desc.thetext:
Use the following code to reproduce:

      tree = new qx.ui.tree.VirtualTree(null, "name", "children");
      this.getRoot().add(tree);

      var model = {name: "root", children: [{name: "#"}, {name: "a", children: null}, {name: "b", children: [{name: "b1"}]}]};      model = qx.data.marshal.Json.createModel(model, true);
      tree.setModel(model);

As you see, a model is created having the following structure:

root
- #
- a
- b
-- b1

The # node does not have a children property and is therefore, rendered as leaf. The b node has a children property and children and is rendered as folder. But the a node has a children array but does not have children. It is rendered as a leaf but I would expect it to be rendered as a folder, even it does not have children.
